lender.occupational_info: The hunger in Brazil is sure to address: where there is poverty and lack of access to basic social rights. Even with the historic mobilization of civil society in the cause and implementation of public policies for food security, there are still all over the country who have no access to food in quantity and quality sufficient to maintain health. Child malnutrition gives the clearest signs of the problem in rural and urban areas. In Rio de Janeiro, the City of God, a survey conducted in 2008 showed that 22% of more than 2 thousand children surveyed were malnourished. (1) In Alagoas, 9.5% of children under 5 years have chronic malnutrition (low height for age) (2). ActionAid bet that the solution to hunger in the country is in stimulating sustainable food production at the local level, increasing the food supply in the region. We also need to enforce the legal mechanisms (laws and public policies) that already exist to ensure that nobody feels hungry.

lender.loan_because: We like to help people out of poverty by giving them more control over their futures.
lender.occupational_info:
We started in Autumn 2009 by wanting to create our own microfinance bank after researching microfinance as part of the IB Geography course. Once we found Kiva, we decided it would be more efficient to use Kiva and concentrate our energy on raising money to lend. At first we decided to raise money by recycling mobile 'phones. This raised our first ¬£1304 in April 2010 as part of the biennial Make A Difference Day. In Spring 2011, we entered a second round of mobile 'phone recycling which raised ¬£1212.50. So far we had raised the money without directly asking people for financial donations, which we liked.
In Spring 2011 a group of 3 students entered the school's Chiara charity competition and won 80% of the prize fund for Kiva (¬£8000!). This has significantly increase our seed fund and we hope that all members of the school will be able to be involved in choosing entrepreneurs to lend to and track their progress.
Our next core funding boost came in December 2011, from a group of pupils who formed their own business, called Icon, as part of the King's Enterprise Challenge. They sourced and sold bespoke clothing such as hooded tops, which they sold to other pupils. They contributed their profit of ¬£240 to our Kiva fund, an especially generous gesture, given how hard they had worked to earn the money.
We were thrilled to pass through the 1000 loan mark around Christmas 2011.
In February 2012, we undertook our next episide of recycling, which involved collecting unwanted CDs, DVDs and computer games. This has yielded over ¬£1000 for our overall fund.
